&lt;h2 id="Economic-Indicator-Basics-Series:-GDP"&gt;Economic Indicator Basics Series: GDP&lt;a class="anchor-link" href="https://johncoughlan.github.io/posts/economic-indicator-basics-series-gdp/#Economic-Indicator-Basics-Series:-GDP"&gt;¶&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;h3 id="A-closer-look-at-U.S.-Gross-Domestic-Product"&gt;A closer look at U.S. Gross Domestic Product&lt;a class="anchor-link" href="https://johncoughlan.github.io/posts/economic-indicator-basics-series-gdp/#A-closer-look-at-U.S.-Gross-Domestic-Product"&gt;¶&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is the first installment in my little series on economic indicators and there’s no better place to start than Gross Domestic Product. GDP is basically the monetary value of all goods and services produced by a country (or region) over some period of time so it’s particularly useful for comparing the size of different economies and analyzing trends in economic growth. We’re going to focus on U.S. GDP and how to analyze the most prevalent trends. 
